# Customer scope and revisions

Canonical source: `app/package_config.py` + `/terms` §2 and §5.

## Revision rounds (hard caps — never promise more)

| Package | Rounds | Turnaround (after intake) |
|---------|--------|---------------------------|
| Foundation | **1** | 5–10 business days |
| Launch | **2** | 7–14 business days |
| Accelerator | **3** | 10–21 business days |

**One round** = one consolidated client feedback message on in-scope deliverables. Multiple emails ≠ extra rounds.

## Not included in any package

- Job placement, guaranteed interviews, or hiring outcomes
- Application submission on the client's behalf
- Ongoing maintenance or retainers
- Interview coaching as a standalone service

## Scope creep → quote or upgrade (not a revision)

- Target role change after build started
- Projects/experience not in intake
- Full redesign or template switch after first draft
- Deliverables outside the purchased tier (e.g. resume on Foundation)

## When editing customer-facing copy

- Pull deliverables, `revision_rounds`, and `excludes_display` from `package_config.py` — do not hardcode counts in templates.
- Checkout and landing must show revision caps before payment.
- If a client asks for "10 revisions" or open-ended changes: cite Terms §5 and their package cap; offer upgrade or paid add-on — do not expand scope informally.

## Operator reference (internal)

`docs/PAID_CLIENT_OPERATIONS.md`, `docs/PRICING_MODEL.md`, `docs/COMPETITIVE_POSITIONING.md`

## Do not copy competitor failures

| Their mistake | Our rule |
|---------------|----------|
| “Unlimited revisions” | Fixed 1 / 2 / 3 — never promise unlimited |
| Interview guarantees | Never guarantee interviews or offers |
| PDF-only delivery | Every tier includes live portfolio deploy |
| Platform lock-in | Client owns GitHub, domain, LinkedIn |
| Vague post-payment scope | Full included/excluded list on `/checkout` |
| Free-review upsell funnel | No bait-and-switch; `/contact` for fit questions |
| Conflicting revision FAQ vs email | One definition: `REVISION_ROUND_DEFINITION` in `package_config.py` |
